      "side": 1,
      "message": "That is an interesting thought.\n\nThe raster code does perform clipping to brings values in-range, but its version fails for exactly the floats this CL is guarding : those that are right near max-float. We could call pathops for the extreme paths, though I have two follow-on thoughts:\n\n1. what is the quality of the resulting values, if some of their \"end-points\" are out in the range where the matissa can\u0027t have much precision?\n2. do we have clients that, on their own, do not want to pay for the code-size of pathops?\n\nRegarding #2 -- I just did a hack, where I included only a tiny subset of pathops/, enough to make us like but returning false for Op(). This saved 440K, which seems pretty significant. (that is a large percentage of Skia itself).\n\nIf we are convinced that there is some value in handling floats that are that huge (i.e. the drawing is still meaningful, see #1), then perhaps we could offer clients to either use pathops for those cases (bringing in 440K) or failing, and let them decide.",
